Fraudulent job postings¶

Due to the large amount of modules imported, we have made a duplicate Google Colab notebook here for ease of running this notebook.

Our objectives and the questions we intend to answer:¶

  • Identify fake job postings by sentiment analysis.
  • Which model is the best, in terms of metric scores, memory used and speed?
  • Identify countries which are associated with fraud postings.
  • Find associated features with a fraudulent and non-fraudulent posting.

Our conclusions and takeaways are located at the end of this notebook.

This project was submitted as part of the requirements of EE0005 Introduction to Data Science and Artificial Intelligence.

NLP pipeline¶

For Natural Language Processing (NLP), we have a slightly different pipeline compared to a numerical/category dataset as per below.
Image source: https://mlwhiz.com/images/text_processing_flow_1.png

For our case, we use token counts with a TF-IDF Vectoriser for our scikit-learn models and word embeddings for our Tensorflow models.

def plot_cat_feature_distribution(feature_name):
    '''Makes a plotly chart with categorical feature\'s distribution.'''
    feature_0f = df[df.fraudulent == 0][feature_name].fillna('Unspecified').value_counts()
    feature_1f = df[df.fraudulent == 1][feature_name].fillna('Unspecified').value_counts()
    
    fig = make_subplots(rows=1, cols=2, specs=[[{'type':'domain'}, {'type':'domain'}]], 
                        subplot_titles=['non-fraudulent', 'fraudulent'])
    fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=feature_0f.index, values=feature_0f.values), row=1, col=1)
    fig.add_trace(go.Pie(labels=feature_1f.index, values=feature_1f.values), row=1, col=2)
    
    fig.update_layout(title_text=f'The distribution of {feature_name}')
    fig.show()

def show_feature1_x_feature2_info(feature_name1, feature_name2, figsize=(12, 4), is_binxcat=False):
    '''Shows info about a combination of two binary/categorical features.'''
    cont_table = pd.crosstab(df[feature_name1], df[feature_name2]).fillna(0)
    prop_table = pd.pivot_table(df, index=feature_name1, columns=feature_name2, 
                                values='fraudulent', aggfunc=np.mean).fillna(0)
    
    corr, p = cramers_v(cont_table.values)
    
    if is_binxcat:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=figsize, sharex=True)
    else:
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=figsize)
    
    sb.heatmap(cont_table, annot=True, fmt='d', ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title(f'Contingency table:')
    if is_binxcat:
        axes[0].set_xlabel('')
    
    sb.heatmap(prop_table, annot=True, ax=axes[1])
    axes[1].set_title(f'Proportion of fraudulent posts:')
    
    fig_title = f'{feature_name1} ' + r'$\times$' + f' {feature_name2} (Correlation: {round(corr, 4)}, p-value: {round(p, 4)}))'
    if is_binxcat:
        fig.suptitle(fig_title, y=1.05, x=0.45)
    else:
        fig.suptitle(fig_title, y=1.05)
    
    fig.show()

def cramers_v(contingency_table):
    '''Cramer\'s V coefficient.'''
    n = np.sum(contingency_table)
    ct_nrows, ct_ncols = contingency_table.shape
    if n < 40 or np.sum(contingency_table < 5) / (ct_nrows * ct_ncols) > 0.2:
        raise ValueError('Contingency table isn\'t suitable for Cramers\'s V coefficient calculation.')

    chi2, p_value = stats.chi2_contingency(contingency_table)[:2]
    corr = np.sqrt(chi2 / (n * (min(ct_nrows, ct_ncols) - 1)))
    return corr, p_value

Metrics¶

We need to beat this dummy classifier (which predicts all rows as 1)!

Classfication accuracy is not a good measurement as our dummy classifier attains a 95.6% accuracy due to the class imbalance. Hence, other metrics are used like AUC-ROC score, Matthews Correlation Coefficient (MCC) and F1 Scores are used.


From this article, F1 is better than MCC for our case. In actuality, we use F2 score to focus more on minimising false negatives, as it is more sensitive to recall due to us wanting our model to identify more fake postings.

$F_2 = \frac{(1 + 2^2) \text{ } \cdot \text{ Precision } \cdot \text{ Recall}}{2^2 \text{ } \cdot \text{ Precision } + \text{ Recall}}$    Click here for source.

Although we might get more false positives, it is okay we want to identify the maximum number of real fake postings, because the fake postings does more harm then missing out on the real postings.


Hence, for this dataset, we will be monitoring the ROC AUC Score and F2 Score.

def custom_metrics(X, Y=df['fraudulent']):

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, random_state=0)
    vect = TfidfVectorizer(min_df=1, max_features=2000).fit(X_train)
    X_train_vectorized = vect.transform(X_train)
    X_test_vectorized = vect.transform(X_test)
    model = LogisticRegression(C=28, solver='liblinear')
    model.fit(X_train_vectorized, y_train)
    predictions = model.predict(X_test_vectorized)
    
    # Print some metric scores
    print('Classification Accuracy\t:', model.score(X_test_vectorized, y_test))
    print('Matthew\'s Corr. Coeff.\t:', matthews_corrcoef(y_test, predictions))
    print('ROC AUC Score\t\t:', roc_auc_score(y_test, predictions))
    print('F1 Score\t\t:', f1_score(y_test, predictions))
    print('F2 Score\t\t:', fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, 2))
    print('\nConfusion Matrix:')
    plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(4, 3))
    sb.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions), annot=True, square=True, fmt='d');

Text cleaning¶

The codeblock below uses regular expression (RegEx) to clean the text fields company_profile, description, requirements and benefits:

  • remove special characters, email and URL
  • aA or a.A --> a A
  • remove punctuations, digits and double spaces
  • convert all text to lowercase
In [36]:
text_fields = ['company_profile', 'description', 'requirements', 'benefits']

for item in text_fields:
    df_cleaned[item] = (df[item].str.replace(r'\\n', ' ').str.replace(r'&amp', ' ').str.replace(r'\xa0', ' ')
                                .str.replace(r'\$str=',' ').str.replace(r'AppKey=*[0-9a-z]+', ' ')
                                .str.replace(r'#EMAIL_[\w]+#', ' ').str.replace(r'#URL_[\w]+#', ' ').str.replace(r'#PHONE_[\w]+#', ' ')
                                .str.replace(r'http[s]?://(?:[a-zA-Z]|[0-9]|[$-_@.&+]|[!*\(\),]|(?:%[0-9a-fA-F][0-9a-fA-F]))+', ' ')
                                # Replace aA / .A to "a A" / ". A"
                                .str.replace(r'(?<=[a-z])(?=[A-Z])', ' ').str.replace(r'(?<=[.,?!:])(?=[A-Z])', ' ')
                                # Remove punctuation, digits, double spaces and convert all to lowercase
                                .str.replace(r'[\+\*=@#<>\(\)\[\]\^_/"-]+', '  ')
                                .str.replace(r'[^\w\s]*', '').str.replace(r'[0-9]+', ' ')
                                .str.replace(r'[\s]+', ' ').str.lower())

df_cleaned[text_fields] = df_cleaned[text_fields].fillna('')
df_cleaned['fraud'] = df['fraudulent']

Remove stopwords¶

Stopwords are common words like "I, the, an" which needs to be removed as they will be counted in during the vocabulary frequency.

In [37]:
from nltk.corpus import stopwords

stop_words = list(get_stop_words('en'))         # About 900 stopwords
nltk_words = list(stopwords.words('english'))   # About 150 stopwords
stop_words.extend(nltk_words)
stop = set(stop_words)

def remove_stopwords(sentence):
    tokens = sentence.split()
    tokens = [token for token in tokens if token not in stop]
    return " ".join(tokens)

for col in text_fields:
    df_cleaned[col] = df_cleaned[col].map(remove_stopwords)

Lemmatization¶

Lemmatization is the act of changing back a word to its base form since the other forms of the word has the same meaning and will only increase the vocabulary count.
Image source: https://medium.com/swlh/introduction-to-stemming-vs-lemmatization-nlp-8c69eb43ecfe

For our case, we found that by using Lemmatization on company_profile, description, requirements and benefits, the scores for all metrics decreased. So, we won't be using it for our models later.

Note: The code below takes 10 minutes to run, so we have provided the lemmatized dataset that we have previously gotten.

Oversampling¶

  • As the proportion of fraudulent postings is very small, we have to oversample it so that the models are able to determine the features better.
  • Oversampling, however, for the test set should not be done as the test set should reflect the real ratio of fraudulent job postings in real life, which is not common.

We now test out which oversampling strategy is the best so that we can use it later.

Source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/smote-oversampling-for-imbalanced-classification/

In [40]:
def oversample_test(sampler, X, Y=df['fraudulent']):

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, random_state=0)
    vect = TfidfVectorizer(min_df=1, max_features=2000).fit(X_train)
    X_train_vectorized = vect.transform(X_train)
    X_test_vectorized = vect.transform(X_test)
    oversample = sampler(sampling_strategy=0.8, random_state=0)
    X_train_vectorized, y_train = oversample.fit_resample(X_train_vectorized, y_train)
    model = LogisticRegression(C=28, solver='liblinear')
    model.fit(X_train_vectorized, y_train)
    predictions = model.predict(X_test_vectorized)
    
    # Print some metric scores
    print('Classification Accuracy\t:', model.score(X_test_vectorized, y_test))
    print('Matthew\'s Corr. Coeff.\t:', matthews_corrcoef(y_test, predictions))
    print('ROC AUC Score\t\t:', roc_auc_score(y_test, predictions))
    print('F1 Score\t\t:', f1_score(y_test, predictions))
    print('F2 Score\t\t:', fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, 2))
    print('\nConfusion Matrix:')
    plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(4, 3))
    sb.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions), annot=True, square=True, fmt='d');

In [45]:
roc_dict = {}
f2_dict = {}

# Use final model and print all metric scores
def skmodel(model):
    model.fit(X_train_vectorized, y_train)
    predictions = model.predict(X_test_vectorized)
    # Print some metric scores
    print('Classification Accuracy\t:', model.score(X_test_vectorized, y_test))
    print('Matthew\'s Corr. Coeff.\t:', matthews_corrcoef(y_test, predictions))
    print('ROC AUC Score\t\t:', roc_auc_score(y_test, predictions))
    print('F1 Score\t\t:', f1_score(y_test, predictions))
    print('F2 Score\t\t:', fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, 2))
    print('\nConfusion Matrix:')
    plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(4, 3))
    sb.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions), annot=True, square=True, fmt='d');
    return model, roc_auc_score(y_test, predictions), fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, 2)

# Loop through the model with different parameters, then return both F1 and F2 scores
def skmodel_loop(model):
    model.fit(X_train_vectorized, y_train)
    predictions = model.predict(X_test_vectorized)
    return f1_score(y_test, predictions), fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, 2)

# Print the results of hyperparameter tuning
def print_metrics(metrics, xlabel):
    f1 = [metric[0] for metric in metrics]
    f2 = [metric[1] for metric in metrics]
    # Semilog or normal plot
    if param[-1]/param[0] > 100:
        plt.semilogx(param, f1);
        plt.semilogx(param, f2);
    else:
        plt.plot(param, f1);
        plt.plot(param, f2);
    plt.xlabel(xlabel);
    plt.ylabel('Metrics');
    plt.legend(['F1 Score', 'F2 Score']);
    plt.title(f'Highest F2 Score at {xlabel} = {param[f2.index(max(f2))]}')

Random forest classifier¶

  • GridSearchCV is a library function in sklearn's model_selection package. It tries all the combinations of the values passed in the dictionary and evaluates the model for each combination using the Cross-Validation (CV in GridSearchCV stands for cross validation) method in order to determine the hyperparameter value set which provides the best ROC AUC score (scoring = 'roc_auc'). 5-fold cross validation is applied in this case.
  • rf_tune is the RandomForestClassifier object used to find best parameter.

Reference:

  1. Hyperparameter Tuning with GridSearchCV
  2. What is Cross Validation in Machine learning? Types of Cross Validation

Performance

  • Beside oversampling method, class weighting is also applied in this case to improve RF classifier's performance as the RF classifier tends to bias towards the majority class. Class weighting imposts a cost penalty to the minority class misclassification by assignining high weight to the minority class.
  • Param class_weight="balanced" will replicate the smaller class until has as many sample as in the larger one but in an implicit way.
  • In the following code, we can see the ROC AUC Score and F2 Score slightly increase/decrease (depending on each run) after class weighting. One possible reason is the data is approximately balanced after oversampling (44.44% fraudulent data), thus class weighting doesn't help a lot in this case.

Reference: Using Random Forest to Learn Imbalanced Data

Simple neural network (using Keras)¶

  • We first convert the tfidf values into a recognisable form that Keras can use.
  • GaussianNoise layers and Dropout layers are added to prevent the model from overfitting
  • F2 score of the predictions is tracked. The model ends training early if the next three F2 scores are lower.
  • The predictions from the epoch with the highest F2 score is then used.
In [63]:
def convert_sparse_matrix_to_sparse_tensor(X):
    coo = X.tocoo()
    indices = np.mat([coo.row, coo.col]).transpose()
    return tf.sparse.reorder(tf.sparse.SparseTensor(indices, coo.data, coo.shape))

X2_train = convert_sparse_matrix_to_sparse_tensor(X_train_vectorized)
X2_test = convert_sparse_matrix_to_sparse_tensor(X_test_vectorized)
In [75]:
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, input_shape=X2_train.shape, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.GaussianNoise(0.2),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(5, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adamax', metrics=['accuracy', 'Recall'])

# Initialise values if not created yet
if 'test_ANN_F2' not in locals():
    train_ANN_F2 = [0.0]
    test_ANN_F2 = [0.0]
    predictions = np.zeros(y_test.shape)
    prev_preds = np.zeros(y_test.shape)
    prev_preds2 = np.zeros(y_test.shape)

# Custom loop to track F2 score for each epoch and end early when the next 3 F2 scores are lower
for i in range(len(test_ANN_F2)-1, 30):
    print(f'Epoch {i+1} \t- prev F2 scores: train = {round(train_ANN_F2[i], 4)}, test = {round(test_ANN_F2[i], 4)}')
    history = model.fit(X2_train, y_train, epochs=1)#, batch_size=32)
    predictions = np.squeeze(model.predict(X2_test) > 0.5).astype("int32")
    train_ANN_F2.append(fbeta_score(y_train, np.squeeze(model.predict(X2_train) > 0.5).astype("int32"), 2))
    test_ANN_F2.append(fbeta_score(y_test, predictions, 2))

    if i >= 3: # Minimum 3 epochs
        if ((test_ANN_F2[i+1] < test_ANN_F2[i-2]) and (test_ANN_F2[i] < test_ANN_F2[i-2])
        and (test_ANN_F2[i-1] < test_ANN_F2[i-2])): # Simulate patience of 3
            print('\n>> F2 Score has decreased, so stopping training and using previous predictions.\n')
            predictions = prev_preds3
            break
        prev_preds3 = prev_preds2
        prev_preds2 = prev_preds
        prev_preds = predictions

Conclusion: Modelling¶

  • The Logistic Regression ^ classifier is the best at detecting fraudulent job posting with the highest F2 score.
  • Fixing the class imbalance is important.
  • Looking at the important features identified by the classifiers, it is confirmed that our hypothesis that company_profile_specified and company_logo are good indicators of whether a job is fraudulent.
  • The simple neural network does not improve our metric scores from Logistic Regression, even after overfitting mitigations. This may be because we do not know how to define our layers in the neural network, so it is not recommended at this stage.


^ Logistic Regression: How it Works

  • Logistic Regression can be used as a classification model
  • Performs linear regression first, output is $z$. Then passes through a sigmoid function, $y=\sigma(z)$, where $\sigma(z)=\frac{1}{1+e^{-z}}$.
  • Distinct boundary at $y=0.5$ (above is 1, below is 0)

  • Is a form of neural network, but scikit-learn takes care of the technical implementation
  • We also use the default L2 regularization, to prevent the model from overfitting to the train data.

Our takeaways¶

For this project, our objectives were as below and we have determined the answers for them.

  • Identify fake job postings by sentiment analysis.

    • We used 6 different models for this classification problem. Certain features were important in identifying whether job postings were fraudulent. These features include the words used in the job postings and the presence of certain fields like company logo and company profile, which were included by using feature engineering.

  • Which model is the best, in terms of metric scores, memory used and speed?

    • Logistic regression is the best in terms of F2 score, speed and the amount of memory used (compared to deep learning).

  • Identify countries which are associated with fraud postings.

    • Top 10 identified by model: 'US', 'AU', 'PL', 'ID', 'PK', 'MY', 'CA', 'ES', 'BH', 'GB'
    • The model has identified the similar countries as listed during EDA earlier (see below). The order however is different, which might be due to the random train-test split that we did earlier.

  • Find associated features with a fraudulent and non-fraudulent posting.

    • See below after final code block

We now use all the features (not capped to 20000 maximum only) so that we can identify the features that are related to fraudulent and non-fraudulent job postings.

  • This codeblock takes a much longer time to run and the F2 score decreased from 0.8791 to 0.8546, hence why we didn't use it for our models earlier.
